  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>One of the melatonin gummies tested by researchers in a 2023 JAMA study contained no melatonin. It did contain 31.3 milligrams of CBD — roughly three times a standard therapeutic dose. The label mentioned neither. A separate product, nominally dosed at 1.5mg, delivered 9mg. Another claimed 5mg and delivered 23.9mg. These aren't outliers pulled to make a point. They are representative of a pattern: 88% of the melatonin gummy products tested were inaccurately labeled, with actual melatonin content ranging from -83% to +478% of what the packaging stated. Tens of millions of American adults take this supplement — many of them nightly, many of them giving it to their children — and the majority of them have no reliable way to know what dose they are actually ingesting.</p>
</section>

<section id="scale-of-use" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Hormone That Went Mainstream</h2>
  <p>Melatonin use among U.S. adults quintupled between 1999 and 2018, rising from 0.4% to 2.1% of the adult population. That's a real number — not a rounding error, not supplement-industry boosterism — documented in JAMA by researchers who pulled data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. More telling than the prevalence figure is the dosing trend embedded within it: since 2005, there has been a statistically significant increase in adults taking more than 5mg per day, a threshold beyond which long-term safety data essentially does not exist. The supplement went from niche circadian-disorder tool to ritual sleep aid, and the doses climbed with the cultural comfort.</p>
  <p>Melatonin is not a vitamin. It is a hormone — produced by the pineal gland, released in darkness, chemically signaling to your body that the day is done. Hormones have dose-dependent effects. That observation should be unremarkable. Somehow, in the context of a product sold next to vitamin C gummies and marketed with phrases like "sleep support," it has become a minority position.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"88% of melatonin gummy products tested were inaccurately labeled — actual content ranging from -83% to +478% of stated dose."</p></aside>

<section id="whats-in-the-bottle" class="reveal">
  <h2>What's Actually in the Bottle</h2>
  <p>The 2023 JAMA study tested 25 melatonin gummy products. Twenty-two were inaccurately labeled. That alone should have generated more coverage than it did. But the finding that earned the least attention is, by most reasonable measures, the most alarming: serotonin was detected in 8 of 30 total products analyzed across both the gummy and pill categories — present in roughly a quarter of tested supplements, at levels the researchers described as potentially clinically significant.</p>
  <p>Serotonin is not an inert byproduct. It is a neurotransmitter with a narrow therapeutic window, implicated in mood regulation, gastrointestinal function, and cardiovascular signaling. In other contexts — combined with certain antidepressants, for instance — elevated serotonin levels can trigger serotonin syndrome, a condition that ranges from uncomfortable to life-threatening. Serotonin is a prescription drug in several countries. In an American gummy bear marketed for sleep, it is an unlabeled contaminant. The mechanism behind its presence is not fully understood; one hypothesis involves the synthetic precursors used in melatonin manufacturing. What is understood is that consumers have no way of knowing it's there.</p>
  <p>The CBD contamination data is almost as disorienting. A 2024 follow-up JAMA letter analyzed 30 melatonin gummy brands. Five declared CBD on the label; in all five, the actual CBD quantity exceeded the melatonin quantity. In the product with the most dramatic discrepancy, the label listed no melatonin and no CBD — and the product contained neither in expected proportions. The supplement aisle has begun to resemble a chemistry experiment no one designed.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Serotonin was detected in roughly a quarter of tested melatonin products — at levels researchers described as potentially clinically significant. The label mentioned none of it."</p></aside>

<section id="regulatory-architecture" class="reveal">
  <h2>This Is Not an Accident. It's a Law.</h2>
  <p>The FDA is not simply asleep. The agency is legally constrained — and that constraint has a name, a date, and a lobbying history. The Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act of 1994, known as DSHEA, effectively redefined the regulatory burden of proof for supplements. Under DSHEA, manufacturers are not required to demonstrate safety or efficacy before bringing a product to market. The FDA cannot require pre-market testing. The agency can act after a product causes documented harm — but it must, in practice, build a case product by product, incident by incident, against an industry that produces tens of thousands of SKUs. DSHEA did not emerge from a vacuum. The supplement industry mobilized consumers and Congress with a campaign arguing that federal overreach was threatening access to vitamins. It worked. What passed was a law that shifted the burden of proof from manufacturers to regulators, and then left regulators without the resources to carry it.</p>
  <p>Melatonin's classification as a dietary supplement — rather than a hormone or a drug, which is how it is regulated in the UK, Canada, Germany, and most of the EU — is a direct product of this architecture. The U.S. made a deliberate policy choice in 1994. The JAMA contamination papers are, in a sense, the bill coming due.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-timing-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>More Isn't Better. Wrong Timing Is Worse.</h2>
  <p>There is a second problem layered beneath the contamination data, and it is mechanistic rather than regulatory. Melatonin does not work like a sleeping pill. It works like a clock signal — nudging the body's circadian rhythm in the direction of the dose timing. Take it at the right time, in an appropriately low dose, and it can help advance or delay the sleep-wake cycle. Take it too late, or in doses far above what the system was calibrated to receive, and the clock shifts in the wrong direction. Grogginess the next morning. Difficulty falling asleep the following night. A circadian rhythm that is now misaligned in a new way, different from the one you were trying to correct.</p>
  <p>Animal models suggest that sustained exposure to supraphysiological melatonin doses may reduce receptor sensitivity over time — the receptors becoming less responsive to both the supplement and to the body's own endogenous signal. Animal models show sustained high doses reduce receptor sensitivity, and while human data is sparse, the mechanism's plausibility demands we treat it as a real risk—not a footnote—for the millions popping these nightly for years.</p>
  <p>StatPearls' 2024 review of melatonin physiology is precise on this point: exogenous melatonin is most effective for circadian rhythm disorders — jet lag, shift work, delayed sleep-wake phase disorder. Its efficacy for primary insomnia is substantially less clear, with controlled studies showing decreases in sleep latency of only a few minutes. For the enormous population using it as a general sleep aid, the evidence is thinner than the marketing suggests. That's a separate question from the contamination findings. But it belongs in the same conversation.</p>
</section>

<section id="children" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Sharpest Edge</h2>
  <p>In 2022, the American Academy of Sleep Medicine issued a health advisory recommending that parents consult a physician before giving melatonin to children. The AASM cited concerns about unknown long-term effects on puberty and development — not hypothetical concerns, but identified gaps in the evidence base for a hormone being given to developing bodies with endocrine systems still in formation. Melatonin is not benign by definition simply because it is endogenous. The question of what happens to a child's hormonal development when exogenous melatonin is introduced, at inconsistent doses, over months or years, remains genuinely open.</p>
  <p>The market has not waited for an answer. Melatonin gummies are sold in children's formulations — often fruit-flavored, often in the same aisle as multivitamins — with dosing information that the JAMA studies have now demonstrated to be unreliable. A parent giving their child a "1mg" melatonin gummy may be giving them 4.8mg. They may also be giving them an unlabeled quantity of serotonin. There is no mechanism under current law that requires the manufacturer to know this before the product ships.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-workarounds" class="reveal">
  <h2>Third-Party Certification Is Not a Solution</h2>
  <p>Third-party certification programs — NSF International, USP — exist precisely because the regulatory framework doesn't require pre-market accuracy. They test for what's on the label. Some of them test for common contaminants. They are a quality signal, not a clinical endorsement, and they are not a substitute for a functional regulatory system. Fewer than a fraction of supplement products on the market carry these certifications. The ones that do cost more, which means the populations least able to absorb that cost are most exposed to the uncertified alternatives.</p>
  <p>The industry's standard response—'choose a reputable brand with third-party testing'—is technically accurate but inadequate as policy, especially since groups like the Natural Products Association argue DSHEA empowers consumer choice while downplaying contamination rates in their own surveys, which conveniently sample only certified products. It places the burden of navigating a broken system on individual consumers, most of whom have no way to evaluate what "NSF certified" actually means versus what it doesn't. It also concedes the point implicitly: if third-party testing is the solution, the problem is that first-party testing is not required. That's not a consumer education problem. That's DSHEA.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The industry's answer — 'choose a reputable brand' — concedes the problem while declining to solve it."</p></aside>

<section id="closing" class="reveal">
  <h2>Where the Problem Actually Lives</h2>
  <p>The JAMA studies are public. The FDA has access to the same data. The contamination findings, the serotonin presence, the CBD quantities that exceed the melatonin content — none of this is hidden. The question is not whether the government knows. The question is whether the political infrastructure exists to change a law that the supplement industry spent a generation lobbying to keep. DSHEA passed with broad bipartisan support in 1994. The supplement industry's annual revenue now exceeds $50 billion, fueled by giants like Nature's Bounty (owned by private equity firm KKR) and lobbying groups like the Council for Responsible Nutrition, which spent over $3 million in 2022 to preserve DSHEA's lax rules. The peer-reviewed evidence has been clear for years. The political will has not.</p>
  <p>The people paying the difference, in the meantime, are the ones who don't know there is a difference to pay — the parents who think they're giving their kid 1mg, the adults who have been taking 10mg nightly for two years without knowing what's actually in their gummies, the people with circadian disorders who need a reliable dose to do the clinical work that melatonin, used correctly, is actually capable of doing. They are not asking for a revolution. They are asking for the bottle to contain what the label says. In any other pharmaceutical category, that is the floor. Here, it remains an aspiration.</p>
</section>

